<div class="article-body" id="Body"><p class="no-indent">1. Brown the meat on all sides to give it—and the bottom of the pan—a flavorful crust and good color.</p><br/><p class="no-indent">2. Sauté the vegetables to allow the moisture from them to evaporate so it will not water down the cooking liquid. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">3. Reduce savory liquids such as wine and broth to give the dish a deeper, richer flavor. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">4. Place the browned meat in a single layer in the pan to promote even cooking. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">5. Bake the covered dish in the oven to provide gentle, constant heat from all angles. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">6. Tent the meat with foil while you’re finishing the sauce. It will help keep it warm until you’re ready to serve. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">7. Strain the vegetables from the cooking liquid. Skimming the fat from the liquid alone helps avoid an oily sauce. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">8. A roux, which is a mixture of flour and butter, thickens the sauce. Stir constantly to avoid scorching. </p><br/><p class="no-indent">9. Stir vegetables back into sauce before serving with the meat.</p></div>
